comment.author: 58584977@N05
comment.text: Fourth of four pages of 16th-century ms. notes recording the main points of a "brevis informatio" (brief instruction) on preaching by the Lutheran pastor and composer Lucas Osiander the Elder on 10 January 1591 in Stuttgart, where he was resident for most of his career. According to his entry in The New Schaff-Herzog Encyclopedia of Religious Knowledge (New York: Funk and Wagnalls, 1910), when preaching, Osiander "disdained all rhetorical ornament, avoided useless controversy, spoke simply and colloquially, with Biblical edification" (v. 8, p. 281). These attitudes are reflected in the informatio which, for example, encourages the preacher to eschew long periods, because his hearers will have forgotten the beginning before he reaches the end. Established heading: Osiander, Lucas, 1534-1604

IX. 9 (Leyden: Elzevir), presided over by Johannes à Marck in 1693. He has a CERL heading.
